Day 29 - 2 days left until the end, 48 hours remain...

Wow, these days go by MUCH slower than I'm used to. At this point I'm gonna have to use sleeping pills to my advantage. Anyway, tomorrow will be the final day, the day that will decide the fate of every participant. Don't feel discouraged though, I have some motivation to keep you going!

- As has been stated in the previous thread, think of each day as a special one. Today is the day before the last day. If you can make it to the final day, there's nothing that can possibly stop you, so focus on surviving until then and imagine the final day as the "clear zone" of course, it goes without saying but don't 'do the thing' then.

Let's go over another question then, given I can only ask two more of these. How has NNN improved your life? I mean, with so much more free time on your hands you get to do things you normally wouldn't even think about, like doing some push ups or doing more house work. For me, push ups have definitely been one of the benefits, but I also get to hone-in on my writing skills making these comments. Story writing is a passion of mine, and it's great to see so much positive feedback on what I've been writing, alongside sparking some interesting discussion (I always love reading your replies!)

I'll try to do more writing after NNN, and will definitely be doing this again next year. Thanks for your support soldiers, this month wouldn't have been nearly as do-able if it weren't for you all. Remember, survive until tomorrow, that is the last day. Alright, good night soldiers! o7

Of course, the Admiral warns all those who venture south of London. For some of the naval forces had been converted to Sequencers following The Dawn Machine's rebellion. I sail along the coast, looking to avoid any unnecessary fights against zee-beasts and pirates.

Hell has brought freedom to the Iron Republic: freedom from all laws, even those of nature. At least the fuel here is cheap.

Not looking to lose my soul, either legally or otherwise, I decide to sail past the city besides Hell's mouth. After some time has passed, down southwest is a bright light unlike anything I've ever seen. Blocking the glorious light is my destination: The Grand Geode. Yet as I get close to it something in me clicked, I change my course. 

The light of the Dawn Machine oozes onto the deck. Its rays bathe the ship. The crew averts their eyes, some drop onto their knees. The light compels me, drawing me in.

I prayed to Salt, Storm, and Stone that I will survive this voyage, for the deep dark zee is unforgiving.
